Video Stitching with Timestamp Overlay (Python/OpenCV)
This repository provides a Python script to stitch multiple .mp4 videos from a folder into a single video per folder, overlaying vertical timestamps based on the filenames.

!!Important Compatibility Note!!
This script relies on OpenCV's ability to write single-channel grayscale .mp4 videos. Newer versions of OpenCV (≥4.12) used with Python 3.13 can fail with the error: FFmpeg: Failed to write frame

To ensure compatibility, use the following versions:
-Software	Version
-Python	3.12.x
-OpenCV	4.8.x (tested: 4.8.1)

We recommend you check Your Installed Versions:
-Check your OpenCV version: python -c "import cv2; print(cv2.__version__)"
-Check your Python version: python --version

Recommended Environment Setup using Conda:
conda create -n opencv48 python=3.12
conda activate opencv48
conda install -c conda-forge opencv=4.8

Features
-Reads multiple .mp4 videos from a folder and sorts them by filename-based datetime
-Converts frames to grayscale
-Skips frames below a configurable brightness threshold to remove black frames
-Overlays the filename as a vertical timestamp on the bottom-left corner of each frame
-Exports a single stitched video per folder with consistent resolution and FPS

Steps:
1. Download most recent .py script

2. Update settings at the top of the script:
parent_dir = r"D:\Transfervideos\mouse1"   # Root folder containing ALL subfolders of videos

3. Run the script:
-Navigate to the folder containing the script: cd path\to\script
(Example: cd C:\Users\LoganLab\Desktop)
-Then run: python stitch_videos.py

Output files will be saved in each video folder with the naming format:

<folder_name>_stitched.mp4

